The shape of the compose file.

The conventional filename is compose-dot-yaml, though the older docker-compose-dot-y-m-l still works. The minimum valid file is tiny: a services block, with one service called web, whose image is n-ginx alpine. That's it. Docker compose up starts it, auto-creating a network for the project and joining web to it.

Everything else is optional structure layered on top. At the top level, you can set a name, which is the project name, defaulting to the directory name. Then comes the services block, which is the heart of every file. Each service can set an image, or a build; ports, for host-to-container publishing; environment, for variables; volumes, for mounts; depends-on, for startup order; a health check, for readiness; and a restart policy. Below the services, an optional networks block declares named networks, though one default is auto-created. And an optional volumes block declares named volumes, just like docker volume create.

The shape to internalise is this. The services block is the only required part, and each service is essentially a declarative docker run. The flags you learned in modules three through five become y-a-m-l keys: dash p becomes ports, dash e becomes environment, dash v becomes volumes, and the restart flag becomes restart. The top-level networks and volumes blocks declare shared resources that services then reference by name.

A few keys pay for themselves early: build, to build an image instead of pulling one; depends-on, for order; and health check, for real readiness. Each gets its own section. But the mental model is simply this: a file of services, each one a docker run written in y-a-m-l, plus the named resources they share.
